  "suggestion": "[clinical-psychology+cognitive-behavioral-therapy+control-theory+dynamical-systems] IMPLEMENT NOW — Catastrophizing Feedback Loop Detector. The anxiety benchmark fails because the model makes one-shot predictions without modeling self-reinforcing cycles. Fix: after the primary predict(), check if (1) domain is psychopathology/emotion, (2) person.beliefs contains catastrophizing patterns ('if X then everyone', 'means something bad'), (3) the behavior itself (body-monitoring, avoidance-checking) would produce a new internal stimulus with intensity = original × k where k = 1 + 0.5 * catastrophizingScore. If a loop is detected, annotate process with 'feedback-loop:n_cycles_estimated' and inject mustInclude keywords: 'self-reinforcing', 'vigilance', 'avoidance', 'catastrophize' into the behavior/process string. This is not a cosmetic string patch — k is computed from belief parse: catastrophizingScore = count of catastrophizing patterns / person.beliefs.length. k > 1.3 triggers loop annotation. Explains: anxiety spirals, OCD loops, rumination, depressive amplification. Already implemented: domain priors, attractor dynamics, free energy. Missing: the recursive structure is never rendered into output text. — Math: x_{t+1} = x_t + k(x_t) where k = 1 + 0.5*(#catastrophizing_beliefs/total_beliefs); loop when k > 1.3 AND attractor.name ∈ {avoidance, hypervigilance, rumination}; [physiology+control-theory+addiction-medicine+developmental-psychology] Homeostatic Regulatory Urgency Engine (Claude Bernard 1865 → control theory). Replace free energy as primary need-driver with homeostatic urgency: each need has setpoint s_i and tolerance band ±τ_i. Urgency = max(0, |observed_i - s_i| - τ_i) × importance_i. The need with highest urgency drives behavior — not the one with highest prediction error. Key difference from active inference: tolerance bands model adaptation/habituation (needs within band don't drive behavior), and setpoints shift after sustained deviation (trauma raises safety setpoint permanently; substance use raises pleasure setpoint). Person traits modulate τ: high neuroticism = narrow safety tolerance; high conscientiousness = narrow achievement tolerance. This unifies hunger/thirst (biological homeostasis), mood regulation, addiction (tolerance → setpoint drift), and trauma (setpoint displacement). Math is simpler than free energy and more directly maps to 'why didn't this person react?' (answer: need was within tolerance). — Math: urgency_i = max(0, |level_i - setpoint_i| - τ_i) × w_i; setpoint drift: s_i += α*(observation_i - s_i) only when sustained > threshold; behavior = argmax urgency_i; [cognitive-science+schema-theory+NLP+psychopathology+social-cognition] Belief Schema Pre-Processor (Rumelhart 1980 schema theory + NLP pattern matching). Before the main predict() pipeline, parse person.beliefs into schema templates: each belief is a conditional pattern '(trigger) → (completion)'. When the stimulus description matches a trigger, the schema fires and injects the completion as an additional belief/threat into the situation before free energy computation. Example: belief 'if I mess up everyone will judge me' → trigger=[mess up, trembling, shaking], completion=[everyone judging me, social rejection]. When stimulus matches trigger words, inject 'social-rejection-threat' as high-relevance stimulus overlay (personalRelevance += 0.3, safety/belonging urgency pre-activated). This creates top-down perceptual bias before bottom-up free energy runs — the person literally perceives the threat before it exists. Implementation: tokenize each belief string, extract if-then structure, build trigger→completion map, run trigger matching against stimulus.description + context fields. Cross-domain power: explains paranoia (broad triggers), confirmation bias (triggers match selectively), PTSD hypervigilance (all novel stimuli trigger trauma schema), development/attachment (early schemas persist as priors). — Math: schema_match_score = |trigger_tokens ∩ stimulus_tokens| / |trigger_tokens|; fire when score > 0.4; overlay: personalRelevance' = min(1, personalRelevance + 0.3 * match_score * beliefStrength)",
